Where an identity matching process is completed, whether successfully or 
unsuccessfully, the relying party shall keep the logs relating to the identity 
matching process and its outcome, including:
(a) the values provided by the user and the relying party;
(b) the date and time of the identity matching process;
(c) any relevant documentation provided as part of complementary methods;
(d) any identifiers or account numbers used.

Relying parties shall retain the logs for a minimum of 6 months and a maximum 
of 12 months for security purposes.

Qualified certificates for electronic signatures shall contain:
(a) indication as qualified certificate; (b) provider identification;
(c) signatory name or pseudonym; (d) validation data; (e) validity
period; (f) unique identity code; (g) advanced signature/seal of issuer;
(h) certificate location; (i) status service location; (j) QSCD indication.

Qualified electronic signature creation devices shall ensure that:
(a) confidentiality of creation data is reasonably assured;
(b) creation data can practically occur only once;
(c) creation data cannot be derived and signature is protected against forgery;
(d) creation data can be reliably protected against use by others.

Qualified certificates for electronic seals shall contain:
(a) indication as qualified certificate; (b) provider identification;
(c) seal creator name; (d) validation data; (e) validity period;
(f) unique identity code; (g) advanced signature/seal of issuer;
(h) certificate location; (i) status service location; (j) QSCD indication.

Qualified certificates for website authentication shall contain:
(a) indication as qualified certificate; (b) provider identification;
(c) natural person name/pseudonym; (ca) legal person identification;
(d) address; (e) domain names; (f) validity period; (g) unique identity
code; (h) advanced signature/seal of issuer; (i) certificate location;
(j) status service location.

Qualified electronic attestation of attributes shall contain:
(a) indication as qualified attestation; (b) provider identification;
(c) entity identification; (d) attested attributes; (e) validity period;
(f) unique identity code; (g) qualified signature/seal of issuer;
(h) certificate location; (i) status service location.

In notifications referred to in Article 24(2), point (a), of Regulation
(EU) No 910/2014, qualified trust service providers shall cover at least
significant changes to: (a) service descriptions, policies, practice 
statements or associated terms and conditions; (b) technical architecture;
(c) hosting; (d) cryptographic techniques; (e) registration and 
identification procedures; (f) organisational structure or governance;
(g) termination plan; (h) financial resources and liability insurance;
(i) trusted list content; (j) third parties and subcontractors.

Notifications referred to in paragraph 1 shall include:
(a) description of the change; (b) planned date and time of the change;
(c) reasons for the change and, where applicable, evidence for the reasons;
(d) where applicable, updated documents.

Qualified trust service providers shall ensure that the termination plan
specifies appropriate procedures and arrangements for at least the following:
(a) termination of qualified trust services including decommissioning;
(b) timely update of trusted list entries; (c) revocation of certificates
unless obligations are transferred; (d) ensuring no further service output
after termination; (e) ensuring record accessibility; (f) addressing
anticipated, unanticipated, partial and complete termination scenarios;
(g) safeguarding subscriber interests; (h) alternative service arrangements;
(i) providing notices to affected parties.

Qualified trust service providers shall ensure that the termination plan
and records associated with it include at least the following documentation:
(a) procedures for the termination of qualified trust services;
(b) procedures for and records of regular review of the termination plan;
(c) audit reports relating to the termination plan;
(d) termination arrangements with third parties;
(e) terms and conditions, practices and policy documents.

The risk management policies shall include at least: (a) overall risk
tolerance level; (b) relevant risk criteria including likelihood, impact
and level; (c) approach for identification and documentation of risks;
(d) process for evaluation of identified risks; (e) process for 
identification, prioritisation and monitoring of risk treatment measures;
(f) process for continuous monitoring of policy implementation.
